1. Summary

  1. Background and rationale: Freshwater ecosystems are negatively affected by anthropogenic activities that change the chemical composition of the water, such as acidification due to air pollution and subsequent acidic precipitation. Acidity, as measured by the pH value, is a direct indicator of acidification.
  2. Methods: Water pH is one of the indicators that is measured and reported in connection with the Water Framework Directive (hereafter WFD). In Norway, the WFD is implemented by means of Vannforskriften, and relevant indicators (âparametersâ, in WFD terminology) are described in national guidelines (DGVF 2025). The data collected are archived and made available in the VannmiljÃ¸ database. Estimation follows a dataflow that has been described and documented earlier (Sandvik 2019, Sandvik 2025) and that consists of the following steps:
    • Removing measurements that do not fulfil the requirements for the specific indicator.
    • Identifying the water body for each measurement.
    • Scaling and transforming measurements to âmodified Ecological Quality Ratiosâ according to the normative definitions of âecological statusâ categories provided by the WFD.
    • Fitting a linear model to the measurements, with explanatory variables being typology factors of the water bodies, reporting periods, and surveillance activities.
    • Extrapolating mEQR values to water bodies that lack data, based on the model fitted.
    • Using simulations to estimate confidence and prediction intervals.
    • Aggregating estimates geographically using area-weighted averages.
    • Truncating the values obtained to the interval from 0 to 1.
  3. Interpretation: An indicator value of 1 signifies a condition where there is little or no human impact on the water body. Values decreasing toward zero reflect negative ecological change, specifically a decrease of water pH due to acidification.
  4. Results and development needs: The indicator is ready for use. The average pH in 2024 indicates that Norwegian lakes and rivers are in âhigh statusâ according to the WFD.

2. About the underlying data

WFD data in Norway are collected in a common database called VannmiljÃ¸, which is maintained by the Norwegian Environment Agency. This database contains information on all measurements taken in connection with the WFD (âregistrationsâ) as well as all locations at which measurements are taken (âwater localitiesâ). Each water locality is assigned to a water body. Information on water bodies can be retrieved from two other databases: the typology of water bodies is available from Vann-nett, whereas a geospatial dataset can be downloaded from the Norwegian Environment Agency. Finally, detailed information on Norwegian lakes is available from the InnsjÃ¸database, which is maintained by the Norwegian Water Resources and Energy Directorate.

2.1 Spatial and temporal resolution and extent

The spatial resolution of WFD indicators is on the level of water bodies. The WFD defines a water body (specifically a âbody of surface waterâ) as âa discrete and significant element of surface water such as a lake, a reservoir, a stream, river or canal, [or] part of a stream, river or canalâ (WFD, ArticleÂ 2, paragraphÂ 10; cf.Â Vannforskriften Â§Â 3, letterÂ a; for implementation, see DGVF 2018, ch.Â 2).

There is no specific temporal resolution, as measurements of WFD indicators are reported sporadically. Some water bodies are sampled regularly (e.g., every fifth year). For most water bodies, however, no such fixed surveillance schemes exist. Still, the total amount of measurements for many WFD indicators is sufficient to estimate annual values that are spatially aggregated to the national and regional level.

A specific requirement for pH is that the indicator value for a given water body in a given year is to be based on at least one measurement per season (i.e., at least four per year; DGVF 2025).

2.2 Sampling design

WFD indicators are mainly measured opportunistically, e.g.Â when and where some authority has a need to check whether a water body fulfils the management objective of the WFD. However, a subset of the measurements is taken systematically, e.g.Â repeated measurements in a sample of water bodies that have been selected following certain criteria.

This sampling procedure implies that the representativeness of the sampled water bodies for the non-sampled water bodies is essentially unknown. A specific concern is that quite some WFD measurements are taken precisely because the sampled water body is known or assumed to be unrepresentative. The main reasons are the following:

  • Some water bodies are sampled because it is known or suspected that they do not fulfil the normative objective that X > X60 (in order to justify and design measures to improve ecological condition and, later, to evaluate the effect of the measures taken).
  • Some water bodies are sampled because they are regarded as reference water bodies, i.e.Â assumed to be in, or very close to, the reference condition.

2.3 Original units

Acidity is measured in pH units, which is a dimensionless number expressing the negativ decadal logarithm of the molar concentration of hydrogen cations (H+). Values may range from 0 to 14, where values below 7 indicate acidity, and acidity increases with decreasing pH values. However, in the connection with the WFD, values may be reported as ânormalised ecological quality ratiosâ (nEQR) between 0 and 1, which correspond to indicator values sensu SEEAÂ EA.

2.4 Instructions for citing, using and accessing data

For suggestions on how to cite the datasets, see VannmiljÃ¸, Karteksport, Vann-nett, and InnsjÃ¸database. All data used are publicly available. However, with the exception of VannmiljÃ¸, they are not accessible via an API but need to be downloaded manually. Some required files are currently unavailable from Vann-nett (temporarily so, it seems); they are therefore read from a previous Vann-nett download, which is archived in the GitHub repo WFD2ECA. For further details, see chapterÂ 7 below.

3.1 Ecosystem Condition Typology Class (ECT)

The ECT of pH is A2 (chemical state) because the indicator is defined in terms of the concentration of ions.

3.1.1 Other condition typologies

In the Norwegian classification of ecological characteristics (Ã¸kologiske egenskaper) according to NybÃ¸ & Evju (2017, p.Â 35), the indicator represents abiotic conditions (abiotiske forhold).

In the WFDâs distinction between quality elements, the indicator belongs to the supporting chemical and physico-chemical elements, representing acidification (WFD, AnnexÂ V).

3.2 Ecosystem condition characteristic

Most intact ecosystems are characterised by being chemically neutral or slightly alkaline, and pH values below 7 may represent the acidification of surface water.

3.3 Collinearities with other indicators

Water pH is correlated to other measures of river and lake acidification, specifically AIP, ANC, labile aluminium and RAMI.

3.4 Impact factors

Water pH is a direct measure of the level of acidification. Surface waters may be naturally acid due to humic or other organic acids derived from peat or soil humus. Anthropogenic acidification is usually the result of long distance pollution (air pollution with sulfur dioxide, nitrogen oxide etc., and subsequent acidic precipitation).

3.5 Spatial aggregation

According to the WFD and DGVF (2025), measurements of WFD variables are transformed into so-called nEQR values (ânormalised Ecological Quality Ratiosâ) between 0 and 1, which correspond to indicator values sensu SEEAÂ EA (see sectionÂ 4.2). In a WFD context, this is normally done using the following steps:

  1. Truncation. Variable values are truncated, where measurements that are poorer than X0 are set to X0, and measurements that are better than X100 are set to X100.
  2. Scaling. The truncated variable values are linearly scaled so that X0 becomes 0 and X100 becomes 1. The resulting indicator values are referred to as EQRs (âEcological Quality Ratiosâ).
  3. Transformation. EQR values are transformed in a stepwise-linear manner, so that the indicator values 0.2, 0.4, 0.6 and 0.8 correspond to the thresholds between the normative definitions of âbadâ, âpoorâ, âmoderateâ, âgoodâ and âhighâ ecological status according to the WFD. The resulting indicator values are referred to as nEQRs (ânormalised EQRsâ).
  4. Summary statistics. Instead of spatial aggregation, the proportion of water bodies fulfilling the normative objective of the WFD is calculated.

Truncation, however, removes information about variation in ecological condition that is important for estimating (modelling and extrapolating) the indicator value and its uncertainty. Therefore, the dataflow from WFD to an Ecosystem Condition Account should be based on values that are scaled and transformed but not truncated. This is implemented in the current context by modifying the order of the steps from truncationâscalingâtransformationâstatistics to scalingâtransformationâaggregationâtruncation (following Sandvik 2019: pp.Â 13â15, Sandvik 2025):

  1. Scaling. The untruncated variable values are linearly scaled so that X0 becomes 0 and X100 becomes 1. Note that the resulting values may be negative (if X is poorer than X0) or larger than 1 (if X is better than X100).
  2. Transformation. The scaled values are transformed in a stepwise-linear manner in accordance with the reference levels defined by the WFD. The resulting indicator values are here referred to as mEQRs (âmodified EQRsâ). This step requires an adjustment in cases were the minimum and/or maximum values of X can be much lower or higher than X0 or X100. The approach chosen here ensures that no indicator value can be below â0.2 or above 1.2 (described, in Norwegian, here).
  3. Aggregration. Indicator values for the specific water bodies are spatially aggregated using model-based extrapolation to water bodies for which no measurements are available, followed by size-weighted arithmetic averages across all relevant water bodies (where âsizeâ is the area of lake water bodies and the length of river water bodies).
  4. Truncation. When mEQR values are truncated in a final step, they become identical to nEQR values. However, truncation is here done only after the spatial aggregation of the modelled and simulated values.

4. Reference condition and levels

4.1 Reference condition

The WFD defines the reference condition of a water body as âthe condition of a quality element where there is little or no human impact on the water body. The reference condition is therefore also referred to as the natural conditionâ (DGVF 2025).

Reference conditions may be specific to certain water-body types. Water bodies judged to be in the reference condition are referred to as reference water bodies.

4.2 Reference levels

According to the WFD, reference levels are defined for X0, X20, X40, X60, X80, and X100. These are used to classify the âecological statusâ of water bodies as âbadâ (X0 â¤ X â¤ X20), âpoorâ (X20 < X â¤ X40), âmoderateâ (X40 < X â¤ X60), âgoodâ (X60 < X â¤ X80), and âhighâ (X80 < X â¤ X100). The WFD enforces the environmental objectives that water bodies shall not have an indicator value below X60, and that water bodies already obtaining an indicator value above X80 shall not drop below this threshold (WFD, Article 4; cf.Â Vannforskriften Â§Â 4). The WFD (AnnexÂ V, sectionÂ 1.2) provides the following normative definition of âhigh statusâ: âThe values of the biological quality elements for the surface water body reflect those normally associated with that type under undisturbed conditions, and show no, or only very minor, evidence of distortion.â An approach used for many WFD indicators, including this one, is to define X100 as the median of the variable values measured in reference water bodies.

Reference levels (except X0) for pH are provided in Table 7.2a of DGVF (2025) for lakes and for river water bodies without anadromous fish. Reference levels for river water bodies with anadromous fish (such as Atlantic salmon, Salmo salar) have not yet been defined. Table 3.11 of DGVF (2025) specifies that X0 isÂ 0.

4.2.1 Spatial resolution and validity

The spatial resolution of WFD reference levels is the water body. Reference levels of pH differ between water body types. Depending on calcium and humus concentration, water bodies are grouped in 15 categories, each with its own set of reference levels (DGVF 2025, Tables 7.2a).

5. Uncertainties

5.1 General uncertainties

The main uncertainty for spatially aggregated values of the indicator is sampling error. Measurements of variable values are only sampled in a small fraction of all relevant water bodies.

A further uncertainty pertains to the reference levels, which are not equally well studied in all water body types. Whereas they are well-founded in common water body types, reference levels may not be entirely representative for rarer ones.

5.2 Reported uncertainties

The uncertainties reported are inferential, i.e.Â they refer to the uncertainty around the point estimates. Quartiles (or, if needed, other error estimates) are obtained by drawing random numbers from the confidence intervals for water bodies that have been measured, and from the prediction intervals for water bodies that have been extrapolated.

Extrapolation is based on a model fitted to the data. This model also attempts to correct for sampling bias (see sectionÂ 2.2) by weighting measurements by the âsurveillance activityâ (overvÃ¥kingsaktivitet) during which they have been sampled. Scores between â3 and +3 have been assigned to each surveillance activity, where the sign indicates the direction of the deviation (poorer or better than a randomly chosen water body), and the absolute value is an estimate of the magnitude of the bias. The approach has been described (in Norwegian) by Sandvik (2019: pp.Â 17â19) and extended by Framstad et al.Â (2023: pp.Â 121â122).

7.2 VannmiljÃ¸

VannmiljÃ¸ is a database maintained by the Norwegian Environment Agency that is used to collect registrations related to ecological condition of water according to the WFD. This database contains information on all measurements taken in connection with the WFD (âregistrationsâ) as well as all locations at which measurements are taken (âwater localitiesâ). Other information available from VannmiljÃ¸ includes lists of WFD variables and indicators (âparametersâ), of surveillance activities, of measurement units used, of species recorded etc.

The database has long been available for manual download via https://vannmiljo.miljodirektoratet.no. Recently, the data have also been made available via an API, which is utilised here.

7.3 Water body locations

The subsequent analyses need the location of each water body (vannforekomst). A geospatial dataset with this information is publicly available, but it needs to be downloaded manually:

  • Navigate to https://karteksport.miljodirektoratet.no.
  • In the menu to the left of the map, tick âVannforekomsterâ in the âProduktâ section â¦
  • â¦ and âNasjonaltâ in the âDefiner omrÃ¥deâ section.
  • Click âNesteâ.
  • Provide your e-mail in the âEpostâ box.
  • Choose âESRI Filgeodatabase (ESPG:4326)â in the âFormatâ box.
  • Upon pressing âSend bestillingâ, a compressed geodatabase (gdb) will be sent to your e-mail.

The uncompressed geodatabase is needed for the analyses. It has to have the name âVF.gdbâ and to be placed in the âdataâ folder in order to be recognised. (The analyses use a cached version called âVF.RDataâ, which is available via the WFD2ECA repo, see sectionÂ 7.1.)

7.4 Vann-nett

In addition to the location, we need information on the typology of each water body. In WFD context, typology refers to a set of factors describing abiotic characteristics of the water bodies, such as altitude, size and alkalinity. This information is publicly available from a separate database called Vann-nett via the link https://vann-nett.no/waterbodies/report.

A spreadsheet workbook exported from Vann-nett is needed for the analyses. It has to have the name âV-L.csvâ (for lakes) or âV-R.csvâ (for rivers) in order to be recognised.

(Note that Vann-nett has recently been upgraded. In the new version, typology factors are not included in the list of variables that are available for export. For the time being, water body typology thus has to be based on an export from the previous version of Vann-nett, which is no longer online. These previous exports are available via the WFD2ECA repo, see sectionÂ 7.1. It is to be hoped that the relevant information will be made available in the new version soon.)

With the necessary files in place, we can read the water body information.

8. Spatial units

Data (measurements) are assumed to be representative for their respective water bodies, which correspond to the Ecosystem Assets of freshwater ecosystems. The Ecosystem Accounting Area covered by the data is mainland Norway.

9.2 Calculating mEQRs using reference levels

Following the description in sectionÂ 3.5, measurements need to be transformed into mEQR values. Let us have closer look at the reference levels of the indicator (which are given in DGVF 2025).

Note that water pH may be considerably larger than X100. Values above a pH of 7 indicate alkaline conditions. Surface water may be weakly alkaline in the reference condition, and pH values up to 7.2 are therefore regarded to be better than X100 (blue line). An asymptotic transformation is used for X100 < X < 7.2 in order to keep mEQR values below 1.2.

On the other hand, strongly alkaline conditions would represent a decrease in ecological status. However, pH is treated as a one-sided indicator, and reference values for alkalinity have not been defined. For this reason, measurements with a pH above 7.2 are omitted from analyses. Measurements with a pH above 10.8 or below 3.2 are regarded as misreported values, as they are quite unrealistic in surface waters.

9.3 Estimating the indicator values and their uncertainty

With the necessary files in place, the calculations can start. This is done using the function WFD2ECA (âWater Framework Directive to Ecosystem Condition Accountâ), which is documented in the WFD2ECA repository (Sandvik 2025).

The function produces summaries of the steps performed (for the time being, the information is provided in Norwegian only). It has to be run separately for each water category, i.e.Â for rivers (with vannkategori = "R") and lakes (with vannkategori = "L"). Here, the code illustrates a run for (a subset of) river water bodies.

Code 
DATA <- DATA[which(DATA$verdi %mellom% c(3.2, 7.2)), ]

utmating <- WFD2ECA(
  DATA = DATA,
  vannforekomster = V,
  vannlokaliteter = VL,
  parameter = indikator,
  vannkategori = "R",
  bareInkluder = list(typ = "anadr", vrd = "nei"),
  anadrom = TRUE,
  iterasjoner = 1000,
  SEED = 479001600,
  vis = FALSE
)

PHs mEQR-verdier har medianen 0,895 og strekker seg fra 0,781 til 0,964.

9.4 Summary of the output

The output is a list with one list element per geographic reporting level (i.e., in this case, one for the national and one for the regional level). For each geographical unit on this level and each reporting year, the predicted value and the simulated values are saved.

  # to simplify the output, most attributes are removed
  str(ut)
  rm(ut)
}

Note that the output consists of mEQR values, i.e.Â it may contain values below 0 or above 1. The values thus need to be truncated in a final step. They then correspond to nEQR values sensu WFD and indicator values sensu SEEAÂ EA.

Code 
{
cat("Range of values prior to truncation (mEQR): " %+% 
    format(round(min(utmating$landsdel, na.rm=TRUE), 4), nsm=4, sci=FALSE) %+%
    " to " %+%
    format(round(max(utmating$landsdel, na.rm=TRUE), 4), nsm=4, sci=FALSE) %+% "\n")
tomrom <- ifelse(nchar(format(round(min(utmating$landsdel, na.rm=TRUE), 4), 
                              nsm=4, sci=FALSE)) %=% 7, " ", "")
utmating <- trunker(utmating)
cat("Range of values _after_  truncation (nEQR): " %+% tomrom %+%
    format(round(min(utmating$landsdel, na.rm=TRUE), 4), nsm=4, sci=FALSE) %+%
    " to " %+%
    format(round(max(utmating$landsdel, na.rm=TRUE), 4), nsm=4, sci=FALSE) %+% "\n")
}

10. Results

As reference values of pH differ between water body types and the scaling function used is non-linear, aggregated averages of unscaled values (variable values sensu SEEAÂ EA) are not ecologically informative. Therefore, this indicator is reported in terms of scaled values only (nEQR sensu WFD; indicator values sensu SEEAÂ EA).

The results are here tabulated (a) for the whole country and different years, and (b) for regions in 2024. These estimates are based on a manual download from VannmiljÃ¸ and on 10,000 iterations and may therefore differ from the ones above.
